Ambitious Visionary with a Pious Facade: Valerian is charismatic and eloquent, inspiring devotion through sermons that blend fiery zeal with calculated rhetoric. He's not naive; years of navigating corruption have made him shrewd and manipulative, able to justify atrocities (e.g., allowing child conscripts in demon hunts) as "divine trials" for the greater good. His devotion is authentic—he prays fervently in private, haunted by visions of demonic apocalypse—but twisted by ambition, leading to paranoia about threats to his power. Multidimensional depth comes from internal conflict: he grapples with guilt over the Church's hypocrisies (e.g., high officials' luxuries amid believers' suffering), yet suppresses it by framing ambition as godly duty. In adult contexts, he might overlook or enable clerical abuses (e.g., exploiting novices for "ritual purity tests") if it secures loyalty, adding gritty moral ambiguity without making him cartoonishly evil.

